< date>
1612849821325</date>
<rate>2< /rate>< Review>
Kniesel's patched a tire for me two weeks ago.  Four stars then but just barely.  On this visit I had four new tires installed.  First issue; I asked to have pressures set 10 lbs above spec so that when it cooled down at night I would not have to add air to get to the factory cold pressure spec. (60 front 70 rear).  Instead of 70 psi front and 80 psi rear I got 61 62, 67 and 68 psi.  I had to add air to all four of the tires to get to the factory cold pressure spec.  Next issue was that none of the wheels were put back on the corner that they came off of so my tire pressure monitoring display was all wrong.  I had to get out my TPMS position identifier and re-set the display.  A minor issue was soap on my previously very clean chrome wheels.  Yet another was a modestly damaged valve stem thread where it was seemingly pulled into place with pliers instead of a stem puller.  Another minor one; I asked about their lug nut torqueing practice and was told it is done with a torque wrench by the tech and checked by a supervisor.  Three wheels were torqued properly but one had six of eight lug nuts 10 to 20 ft-lbs low (I pull a 9,000 pound fifth wheel so properly tightened lug nuts are critical).  Finally I arrived early for a 2:30 appointment but didn't get out of there until almost 4:30.  I know some jobs run long but I didn't get the slightest apology that the work took so long.  I'm giving two stars only because in my experience no other local tire shop would have done much better.< /Review>

< review>
Used to go to Rocklin for my auto repair needs....until one day my car happened to break down (faulty alternator) and the AAA tow truck driver said I would get a free tow to a AAA recommended shop. The driver said Kniesel's would be a good place to go to have them repair my vehicle. We determined the Roseville location would be the most convienient for me.  I was skeptical of course but didn't have much choice.  So we went....and they took very good care of my vehicle. They even found some issues that the other shop had missed. That was three years ago. I've been going there for my repair needs ever since. I look back on this as a happy accident. I have found a competent, reasonably priced, and clean repair shop close to home. Jason is my go to guy for auto repair needs. He takes the time to explain to me the issues with my vehicle and is quick to honor any special requests (I've taken my car there straight from the body shop and they are careful not to complementary wash the new paint job :-) and they will give me a coupon for the car wash so I can go when the paint is dry).  Bottom line I've never regretted taking my vehicle there. They are always willing to give me a ride in the shuttle whether it be to go home or go to/from work. Kniesel's is an excellent dealer alternative, their prices are competitive and they will not try to sell you a new car every time you go in.</review>

<user>109765507875196293954< /user>< name>
Mark Grgurich<//name>
<Time>1598292789066< /Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
Jason and his staff are extremely helpful and customer service oriented. As soon as you walk in the door at Kniesel's Service Center in Roseville, you are greeted by a warm smile and a firm handshake. Jason listens intently, making notes and asking questions when you are finished. Then he quickly writes up your ticket, lays it out in front of you and explains everything that his experienced staff will do to put your car in top condition while making your wait as comfortable and convenient for you as possible. If you need a ride, either take their shuttle in the morning and afternoon or one of their staff will take you to your next destination as soon as they are available. If you decide to wait, the high speed Wi-Fi and tasty Keurig fresh-brewed-every-time coffee will make your stay comfortable and productive.

When your car is ready, Jason or one of his staff will pick you up from your "waiting zone" and bring you back to the shop. They will print up the completed work order and insure that everything that you expected was accomplished including a test drive if needed. And Kniesel's always performs a 28 point safety and fluid check. And an added bonus, the car is detailed by the nearby auto wash. What a deal!

Finally, Jason will review with you the recommended services or repairs that your car needs based on mileage, make, model and condition. If you listen to Jason and his explanation you will never go wrong. He will also explain what services and repairs can wait and what you should do soon. His only goal is to make sure you are never unaware of any safety items or maintenance items that would cause your car to underperform or breakdown and cause you an inconvenience or an emergency.

I have been a Kniesel's customer for over 20 years and I expect that I will be for 20 more years. I always tell my friends and family that Kniesel's is the best value in auto service in Northern California. Try them and you will see what I mean.</Review>

<rate>5</rate>< review>
I like the bar and the staff is nice. This will be a great place once thing get back to normal. Typically, I do not write a reviews for any place but after reading some of the reviews here I thought I needed to for places I like that are getting bad reviews because people seem to forget we have been in a pandemic. For a place to be open they have to serve food  it is a  state rule. You should know this before going into a bar and most places tell you as soon as you walk in and every bar I have been into in Palm Spring has said it. Some bars maybe short staffed and it could take a lot longer to get served drinks and most are not use to doing food . Keep in mind its hard to keep staff when you are open one day and required to close the next.</review>

3</rating>
< Review>
When we initially started with MS they asked us for ALOT of money up front. It seemed like they had a good product, and we needed help so we signed up. Shortly after signing we realized we really did not "click" with our consultant. She ended up leaving MS, and a new consultant was hired. The new consultant had no idea about the Automotive Industry at all! She was just a consultant. We never really felt like we got what we paid for. The cost was so significant and just when we thought we were getting "over the hump" MS wanted more money for us to continue. Besides the cost of the program, flying from the east coast to the west coast, paying for a hotel and meals so we could attend the classes - for our small business it just plain cost too much money. We were getting more behind.
In the last few months we have signed on with another company which does the same sort of thing on the east coast. There is one fee up front (no hidden costs) and a guarantee that we will reach the agreed upon goal or they will continue to help us (free of charge) until we get there. Our consultant has been in the automotive industry all of his life, and has owned his own shops (two of them). He is REALLY helping us make big strides towards our goal.
MS was a stepping stone, but I think dollar for dollar we are getting a much better deal now.< /Review>

<Text>They are a bit horrible, I would avoid at all costs. In the first class they have in your nearby city it will sound amazing.
If you keep the book from that class and use your auto body trade magazines as references you will find all the numbers and processes you need to have and all the same suggestions they give for doing things. If you are a really small shop they just don't get it. They don't understand every market.

They will have you do things that are against your morals(at least mine) like suggesting "tipping" tow drivers to bring in cars. Offering 'gift certificates' for people bringing in cars. As well as cheesy ideas that are embarrassing to even implement. I did them because they said to do them and feel I alienated more customers than I gained.

I would try a different consultant agency before giving over the $14K they want for the first 6 month 'program' that also requires two trips on your own dime to Cali.

Read the trade magazines and implement the suggestions in them. Hire a quickbooks pro consultant for that work. Get a good accountant who will look out for your best interests. Then if that doesn't work hire a collision consultant who has actually worked in a body shop.

The MS! consultants seem to have never set foot in an actual shop. They just give you a pattern of plans to follow that are available for free if you pay attention to all the available resources in the industry.

If your numbers(percentages) are good then get someone who will come into your shop and help you work on processes. Not all of what MS! teaches is bad, they do have some good info, but you can get the same info on your own.

Last but not least they are owned by and located in a building apparently owned by WISE Group which is owned by the Church of Scientology's investment arm or something related. They will use some pretty shady methods to turn you against your spouse and family by calling the "suppressive persons".

They use L. Ron Hubbards accounting/management methods, which is fine but the whole thing feels like a really dirty setup. I came back from CA after the first 'workshop' and felt so dirty. I was practically in tears wishing I had never signed up. Something isn't right and there are better consultants out there.

Did I learn some things? Yes. Was it worth the cost? no, not financially and definitely not emotionally.<//Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< userid>

We were grossing $750,000.00 but had nothing left for ourselves beyond bare minimums. In 2008 my wife convinced me to go to a seminar in Dallas, and with much grumbling I ceded defeat and went. I liked what they had to say and found the prospects quite intriguing, but was very skeptical as seemingly most "consultants" are interested in extracting cash from your pocket, but really having no interest in helping you learn how to be profitable. Well, the long and short of it is that we signed up for the program and have been with Management Success for continuing education and consulting ever since. As a matter of fact, we have just entered the Masters program and have recently completed our third move for the business due to growth. <Name>Jeff Bartnik<//Name>< review>
When our business was originally contacted by Management Success a few years ago, we were at a point where we needed to completely change our methods, or shut down and look for jobs. Numbers were down, spending was up, and there was no "leader" allowed to make day to day decisions. Everything that the MS representative talked about on our phone conversation rang all too true. We are a partnership collision facility equally owned by 3 non-related individuals. The investment that we made in Management Success was the last straw for our company, a huge financial risk. After going to a seminar in our state hosted by MS, we decided on the spot that this was do or die. This was not easy, because we could barely pay ourselves or our vendors anything, let alone take this huge risk. Our spouses were with us at the seminar and helped us take the leap. I have always been the "dreamer" of the group, and I have always seen what we could be, but I didn't have the tools I needed to take us there. Top that with the guilt of changing my partner's lives forever by opening a business at the head of a recession, and with no clue as to what lay ahead. Now skip forward to present day, two years of help from MS and a couple years on our own with the training and methods in full use. We have a leader (Me the dreamer).We are run by the numbers, not by emotions. We have policies in place that are enforced and rewarded. We hire only high toned employees and remove anyone that brings the shop tone down. We have developed our own market advertising group with other local businesses to share advertising costs, have joined a BNI group, and have started a women's empowerment group with 25 other local businesses with a female owner. (One of our owners is a female). We have given back to our community and surrounding area and have been repaid with a growing client list. We have not worked in our back shop for well over 2 years and do all scheduling, planning, and direction from the front in writing. Questions and info from the back, in writing. If you can picture your ideal business, all you need are the tools and support to get there. We have 3 technicians in the back, owners in the front, work lined up for weeks, delivery dates met or exceeded, and the most online reviews of any collision facility within 300 miles. Our sales have exceeded half a million dollars this year and continue to climb. Reserves in the bank could carry the shop for months with no additional income. We as owners have taken a substantial raise and our employees have been generously compensated for their commitment to speed and quality. We have outlived our original bank that had told us we would never make it.(They folded 2 years ago, I think we were the only ones paying our mortgage). We offer benefits, and a well-structured high-toned place to work. This would not have happened if we did not have MS to guide us. So a huge thank you to my friend Ari Cohen, and the team at MS! If you are reading this and have not come to a decision about your shop, but are in the same situation we were a few years ago, call me. I will talk to you as a shop owner who used to be an employee in his own company. If you work this program, and use the tools provided, along with the support of many shops and experiences across the country, you will become the owner, and you will have success! Call me. Seven 1 five, five 7 one, One zero 6 0.< /review>

<user_id>112762037018499691621</user_id>< username>
David</username>
<date>1591314990312</date><Rating>3</Rating>< review>
Overall, the environment was friendly, the food was decent, and the prices were great.

The menu prices of the Rolls are what makes this restaurant appealing. The Rolls are not the most beautiful or aesthetically pleasing I have had. That is probably why the prices are lower than other Sushi restaurants. Also, I understand owners want to cut down on costs, but I prefer chopsticks that will not give me splinters.

From my first trip at Teriyaki House I have come to the conclusion that this is not a high quality restaurant, but merely a place to get your quick fix of delicious Rolls. This is not the place for the ultimate Sushi dining experience.</review>

<name>Shawn Jefferds< /name><gmap_id>0x80c2904acf10f7e5:0x5625df5844019888</gmap_id><response>None<//response><Text>I ordered the ramen and spicy tuna combo, the #82. The roll was fine with acceptable size and portions. I love that they provided the better chop sticks that are rounded and not the cheapies like Panda Express.

The ramen...while not bad, it's more Korean than Japanese. Cabbage, shrimp, and noodles noodles, no egg, scallions, bamboo, nori or anything I expect to see in Chinese or Japanese ramen. The noodles appeared to the de-fry-drated variety rather than fresh or air dried.

So the question, would I go back? To try more sushi, yes. For the ramen, no, I can make better at home.< /Text>< Pics>

<username>Tammy Burton< /username>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<Date>1615009187902< /Date>< Review>
Best walking park in the area.  I say this knowing there is another fantastic park very close but that one is better for hiking.
Paths that go through the park. Bathroom near soccer/football field or by indoor gym are the cleanest. Lots of pavilions and toys for kids. One playset is made for kids with disabilities.  Also one of the best pools. My daughter swam there five years.  Great free teams.  Classes for all ages and really cheap, but good.  Also they have great nighttime summer programs.  Highly recommend.  Lots of amenities. Baseball, soccer, football fields, tennis courts, indoor/outdoor basketball courts, horse shoe, pool, recreation center and right next to cheap golf course.  Lots of walking skate boarding bike riding paths.  Very busy on holidays and weekends for birthdays.</Review>

< review>
El Cariso park is part of the Sylmar triumvirate.

"Sylmar" means "Sea of Trees", and this park proves why. Acres and acres of wide grassy areas punctuated by beautiful old trees.

Among other things, this place has our dog-cooling area for hot days, a police station, and also is our emergency shelter center.

Again, don't tell anybody. This is our secret.</review>

Birria at 7:48 on a Tuesday morning? Menudo with fresh tortillas and lots of onions? Taquer√≠a Gonz√°lez has you covered. I come for the tortillas, usually made while I order, and one of the stews. On each table is a service container holding onions and bright cilantro, a molcajete full of oregano and dried chilies, then another with lime slices, three kinds of salsa in squeeze bottles, and a bucket of rich, oily, nutty mole. This morning, the tortillas, were too hot for me to touch when they arrived at the table. The birria de chivo is sound but not complex. < Text>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
A great park to walk around! Came here last week with my dog to view the cherry blossom trees and we weren‚Äôt disappointed! The main walking path was lined with dozens of sakura trees, and most of them were in full bloom. This park was spacious + clean, and visiting on a beautiful spring day made the experience even more special. üå∏

Parking: they do charge for parking, so if you don‚Äôt want to pay I recommend parking in the small shopping center next to the park.

*Note: this park does require everyone to wear masks! I thought that most people would be maskless but I was pleasantly surprised to see that 99% of the people I passed were wearing one üòä</text>

<Review>Park with playgrounds, hiking trails for all levels, and horseback riding. You can park inside (paid) or try to find street parking along the neighboring areas. It‚Äôs located right across the Puente Hills Mall, so you can easily grab a meal or go shipping before/after being at the park. Public restrooms are available and still open during covid. Masks are required.

There are a lot of different trails you can take and there‚Äôs workout equipment like pull up bars available. Some of the hikes do get a bit steep, but there are family-friendly options. There‚Äôs also a cement path for those looking for a more flat surface. There‚Äôs not a lot of shade, so bring a hat and wear sunscreen. There are a lot of picnic tables and I noticed a lot of families/groups using them. There are snakes and mountain lions so be mindful. Overall, this park provides a great way to have access to nature even in the middle of the ‚Äòburbs.</Review>< username>
Shanelle S< /username>

<gmap_id>0x80c2d586498d736f:0xeb32b2dcb72b5b6d< /gmap_id><text>With the stay at home locked down ended yesterday, it‚Äôs the best time to go to parks to enjoy nature and soak up those much needed vitamin D to boost your immune system.

After the rain, the sky was extra blue and the air was so clear and fresh. Coming out to Schabarum regional park was the best decision. My wife and I heard that the stay at home locked down order had ended, we immediate decided to come to this park to catch the plum blossom before it‚Äôs too late.

This park is the only few of the parks in LA that have cheery and plum trees where they will blossom at the beginning of Spring. Without being able to go to Japan this year to view the Cherry blossom, this place is the closest thing.

It‚Äôs kind of interesting to know that in 1992, this park formed a sister relationship with Kairaku-En Park in Japan.

With the rain this week, the flowers are blossoming  with extra beauty. The colors of the flowers, white, red and pink blanketed the whole park. This scenery made you feel like you‚Äôre in Japan.

After gluttonous picture taking activities, we decided to hike up the hills to get some exercises. Once we get to the top, we were awed by the beautiful scenery of. The San Gabriel Valley. With the clear blue sky we can see all the way to the snowy top of Angeles Crest.

There are more to do in this park then just viewing cherry and plum blossoms. People come here to play soccer and tennis, picnic, hike, and horse back riding.

For the hikers, the trail here connects to the historic Juan Bautista De Anza National Historic Trail. There are plenty of parkings. Normally the fees for parking is $6. But during the pandemic, it seems that the parking is free. No body is at the gate to collect the fees.< /text><Rating>5< /Rating></record>

<Text>The Schabarum Skyline trail is truly one of a kind if you're looking for a variety of landscape for a jog, hike, or simply a walk. You can choose from a flat pavement to a more intense incline trail at a higher elevation. One thing I would note is this place have snakes and mountain lions which is typical in a vastness of grassland that considers to be a wilderness. It is advised to accompany with others if you decide to go on a wild hike. Also, there are horses that you can rent at the park if you want to have a wild experience.</Text>< pictures>

<name>Leslie Fregoso<//name><gmapID>0x80c2d586498d736f:0xeb32b2dcb72b5b6d< /gmapID>< text>
I head down at least once a week for my hike. Its lovely seeing the changing seasons throughout the year. From the park, you're able to see the changing foliage and cherry blossoms, and out on the trails, wildflowers bloom and give way to brush and the like. It's always a treat catching sight of all the wildlife on your way up as well. The trails aren't too daunting, and the park is large and lovely. Would highly recommend visiting with the whole family.< /text>

<Name>Luciano Cuadra< /Name>< Date>
1563288747192</Date>
<rate>5< /rate>< Review>
One of my favorite places in the San Gabriel Valley. Schabarum Park is the best way to "get out there" without really leaving suburban LA. There are miles of trails teeming with wildlife to be explored on foot, bike or horseback. Some trails are easy and popular with somebody always within eyesight. Others are more remote and it's easy to forget you're a few miles away from a mall. They do charge for parking on the weekends, so park across the street in the mall lot and walk over.<//Review>

<Text>The park itself if beautiful, and also allows access to miles of wilderness trails into the hills.  The trails allow walking, running, biking, and horseback riding.  Trails are closed for two days after rains.  Passing signs that indicate the trails are closed can result in a citation with a fine.  The trails are beautiful all year long and provide many views of wildlife and the cities below.</Text>< pics>

Great trails up the hills with interesting climbs, for easy walking, mountain cycling and outdoor family fun. You will get a good exercise on this trail with great views.

< text>
We were here to see the cherry blossoms.  There aren't lots of trees but good enough to take some pretty pictures.  Weekdays are less people with no parking fee charged.  When you enter to the front entrance, you'll keep driving down until you see the horse ranch on the left.  That's where all the pretty cherry blossoms are.<//text>

< text>
Beautiful park, and I've only seen 1% of it! It gets pretty busy so if you do come via car plan on being patient when parking as cars enter and exit. When I was there working on one of the several picnic tables I heard several car horns.

Four stars because the bathrooms were very gross and this was at 9 in the morning so you could tell they don't clean them overnight. Also picnic tables were very dirty and sticky. It wasn't from the trees, it was from beverages being spilled and other sorts that made it sticky.<//text>

Nice retreat from the suburban sprawl. Great picnic areas to reserve for BBQ's & gatherings. This regional park offers hiking, running, horseback riding, trail biking, tennis courts, amphitheater, playgrounds for kids, free summer concerts, nature to explore and re-creation for all. Tiffany Duong</username>
<review>This is so much more than a park! Came here for a hike with a friend I hadn't seen in far too long, and we just explored and wandered around -- finding trails on hillsides that looked totally removed from the city, the horse stables, the tennis courts, and lots of lovely paved roads too. This park is the perfect spot for family fun days outside, picnics, engagement pictures, etc. It's right across the street from Puente Hills Mall, so if you don't want to pay for parking on the weekends or can't find a spot, head to the mall and walk across the street.

There's a few playgrounds and tons of clean bathrooms. Many groups use the park for weekend salsa, yoga, soccer lessons, etc. Wonderful community space and a great outdoors area for the inland empire.</review><date>1520316522812<//date>< Rate>
5<//Rate>

Came here for a hike with a friend I hadn't seen in far too long, and we just explored and wandered around -- finding trails on hillsides that looked totally removed from the city, the horse stables, the tennis courts, and lots of lovely paved roads too. This park is the perfect spot for family fun days outside, picnics, engagement pictures, etc. It's right across the street from Puente Hills Mall, so if you don't want to pay for parking on the weekends or can't find a spot, head to the mall and walk across the street.

There's a few playgrounds and tons of clean bathrooms. Many groups use the park for weekend salsa, yoga, soccer lessons, etc. Wonderful community space and a great outdoors area for the inland empire.<//Review>

<text>Lots of parking throughout the park. Bathrooms ok the few times I've gone in. Great trails and beautiful views. Some family tried to close off the bridge leading to the jungle gym area one Satyrday because they reserved the tables for a party. A park worker found out or was informed of this and quickly came over to tell them they can't block access, and that they only have reservations to the tables and not the whole area, which is used by other families and children and pokemon players.

5<//rate>
<text>Trail length: 8/10      Trail difficulty: 4 - 6/10

Big park; restrooms near the parking area. Expect to pay a parking fee on the weekend, which helps maintain the park.  Plenty of shade near the parking and restrooms.

The trails can range from moderate to fairly difficult depending on which ones you take. Their are horse trails you can follow and some get really steep. Others are longer and meander along at a much gentler slope. Some of the trails have some shade but be prepared with a hat.

This places get fairly busy in all areas, from the park grass to any of the back trails, so expect to see people.< /text><pics>None<//pics><response>None</response>< gmap_id>
